    "summary": "CONFIRM — context-dependent, both nothingness and void appropriate",
    "content": "**CONFIRM** — context-dependent, both acceptable.\n\nFrom an existentialist perspective, these two English words do genuinely different work:\n\n- **\"Nothingness\"** carries the Sartrean/Heideggerian weight: le néant, das Nichts. It is active, confrontational — the nothingness that annihilates meaning, the absence that makes freedom possible. When the author discusses 虚无主义 (nihilism) or the collapse of metaphysical foundations, \"nothingness\" is the right choice because it names the condition that nihilism reveals.\n\n- **\"The void\"** is more spatial, more atmospheric — it evokes the absence left behind, the vacancy after something has departed. When the author uses 虚无 to describe what remains after the highest values have been lost (the ruins of metaphysics), \"the void\" captures this desolate landscape better.\n\nThe author's own usage supports both senses. Forcing a single default would flatten a real distinction. The translator should choose based on whether 虚无 in a given passage is functioning as (a) the philosophical concept of nothingness-as-such, or (b) the experiential condition of finding oneself in a void.\n\nAgreed on NEVER using \"emptiness\" for 虚无 — that must remain reserved for 空."
  }
